MARKET BY TYPE
Bacillus thuringiensis (Bt) is a spore-forming bacterium that produces insecticidal crystal proteins known as delta-endotoxins. These toxins selectively target a wide range of insect pests, making Bt-based biopesticides a popular choice for integrated pest management programs. There are different types of Bt strains, each with specific target pests.

Bacillus thuringiensis Kurstaki (Btk) is the most widely used strain and is effective against lepidopteran pests such as caterpillars, moths, and butterflies. Bacillus thuringiensis Serotype Israelensis (Bti) is effective against mosquito and black fly larvae. Bacillus thuringiensis Aizawai (Bta) is effective against beetles and caterpillars, while Bacillus thuringiensis Tenebrionis (Btt) is effective against beetle larvae. Other types of Bt strains are also available, each with its specific target pests. These different types of Bt biopesticides provide farmers with a wide range of options for managing pest problems, leading to an increased demand for Bacillus thuringiensis in the market. Additionally, the high efficacy of Bt-based biopesticides in controlling insect pests and their low toxicity to non-target organisms have contributed to their increasing popularity in agricultural, forestry, and public health sectors.

